<TEXT>
sen bill bradley breezed to victory tuesday 
in a barely contested democratic primary and will face republican 
christine todd whitman in the november general election 
with 65 percent of the precincts reporting bradley had 114942 
votes or 94 percent to 7354 votes or 6 percent for daniel 
seyler a political unknown 
mrs whitman former president of the state board of public 
utilities and a former somerset county official had no primary 
opposition 
at an appropriately lowkey victory reception in woodbridge 
bradley said im very pleased to again be the standardbearer for 
the democratic party in the senate election 
seyler 35 of phillipsburg spent about 1300 of his own money 
and raised 8357 from contributors in a campaign whose major issue 
was limiting federal officeholders to 12 years in office 
democratic gov jim florios gubernatorial opponent rep james 
courter who lost in a landslide didnt seek reelection to his 
12th district seat 
state sen richard a zimmer won the republican primary for 
courters seat defeating former new york giants receiver phil 
mcconkey and two other candidates with 67 percent of the precincts 
reporting zimmer had 40 percent of the vote to 30 percent for 
mcconkey and 28 percent for assemblyman rodney frelinghuysen who 
had been considered the favorite to win the nomination 
businesswoman and philanthropist marguerite chandler defeated 
little known james j cleary in the democratic primary for the seat 
</TEXT>
