<TEXT>
while other world leaders fight to stay 
in power and some try to fend off reform the head of the worlds 6 
million tibetans has the opposite problem 
the dalai lamas people are uncomfortable with democracy and do 
not want him to retire as their political leader 
but then most other political figures arent considered living 
gods 
i am insisting on stepping down the dalai lama said in an 
interview it is of greatest urgency that democracy comes to us 
it is the most creative way for the human spirit 
in his ornate parlor overlooking the snowcapped himalayas the 
dalai lama predicted communism soon would fall in china and his 
followers would return to their homeland within 10 years 
tibetans believe their mountainous region with its unique 
culture should be an independent nation china claims tibet has 
been part of its territory since the 13th century 
to prepare for their return the dalai lama said tibetans must 
embrace democracy and shed the idea that he is a god 
it is proving difficult there is strong conservative opposition 
to the dalai lamas plans to democratize his governmentinexile and 
few if any tibetans seem willing to abandon the belief that his 
holiness is divine 
that belief has made tibetans lazy said the 54yearold 
buddhist leader who won the 1989 nobel peace prize they think i 
will do everything for them 
tibetans circle his residence pausing to clasp their hands in 
prayer elderly women limping with age climb steep grades to gaze 
at his compound whispering 10000 years to his holiness 
tibetan buddhist tradition holds that the first dalai lama born 
in 1391 was a reincarnation of chenresi the buddhist god of mercy 
subsequent dalai lamas are revered as reincarnations of their 
predecessors 
the current dalai lama the 14th was chosen in 1936 after a 
series of visions indicated the leader would be found in a house 
with turquoise tiles in eastern tibet 
when he first told tibetans of his wish to give up his political 
position the dalai lama said many people were shocked and they 
told me i should not say this kind of thing 
but i continuously spoke out he said with a playful grin 
he remains a reluctant politician a man of the spirit not of 
law or intrigue clothed in maroon and saffron robes and wearing his 
everpresent tinted glasses the dalai lama chuckled cracked jokes 
and reached out to squeeze the hand of a reporter as he made a point 
i am just a tibetan monk he said running his fingers over 
wooden prayer beads i would rather go to an isolated monastery 
and pray now i have no time for prayer i am always busy busy with 
the affairs of this world 
</TEXT>
