<DOCNO> AP900605-0007 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a scandal involving money and secrets 
from taiwan has started a fight in the tibetan independemce movement 
that threatens gains made since the dalai lama its leader won the 
nobel peace prize last year 
the scandal has alienated many tibetan refugees causing what one 
young tibetan called a big gap between us and our leaders 
on one side are liberals who favor talks with china and making 
the tibetan movement more democratic the dalai lama spiritual and 
temporal leader of the worlds 6 million tibetans leads this group 
on the other are conservatives who oppose contacts with the 
chinese and attempts to reform the governmentinexile conservative 
buddhist monks and older tibetan officials lead them 
its a little irancontra scandal said tendzin choegyal the 
dalai lamas youngest brother to the average tibetan this is a 
very confusing and troubling time 
tattered wall posters along the road to this retreat in the 
himalayan foothills attest to the problem 
traitors you have sold out tibet they read china lovers 
we will never forget your deeds 
both chinas must be laughing their heads off said an 
editorial in the tibetan review the movements official publication 
the scandal emerged last year when tibetan officials began 
accusing each other of being on taiwans payroll 
it revolves around the mongolian and tibetan affairs commission 
a taiwanese government agency like its communist enemy in beijing 
the government of taiwan claims tibet is part of china and rejects 
tibetan independence 
since 1959 when the dalai lama fled china after an abortive 
uprising and set up headquarters in dharmsala taiwan has donated 
hundreds of millions of dollars to tibetan groups according to 
sonam tobgyal spokesman for the exile government 
he said the taiwanese agency aims to convince tibetans to break 
with the governmentinexile which taiwan denies 
gene jy chang head of the agency said it had given much less 
to the tibetans an average of 300000 a year 
in an interview in taipei chang acknowledged some tibetan 
refugees were antichinese not merely anticommunist but said the 
commission would like to improve its relations with dharmsala 
tobgyal said the commission had become increasingly active in 
recent years financing a tibetanlanguage newspaper in calcutta 
building monasteries in nepal and granting scholarships to tibetan 
students 
the main aim of the money has been to create disharmony among 
tibetans tobgyal said 
he claimed taiwan paid independence activists to return to tibet 
and stir up trouble thus violating the dalai lamas policy of 
nonviolence taiwan denies the charge 
the reasons for taiwans alleged meddling are not clear 
it could seek to foment further political turmoil on the chinese 
mainland by encouraging protests in tibet but also might be 
currying favor with beijing by trying to weaken the tibetan 
movement taiwan recently abandoned its no contact policy toward 
the mainland 
a further complication is the relationship between the security 
agencies of taiwan and the tibetan exile government 
since 1986 dharmsala has provided taiwan with details about 
tibet in exchange for taiwanese intelligence about political changes 
in china tobgyal said he defended the exchange but granted that 
it raised eyebrows among tibetans 
in a speech to his cabinet in january the dalai lama said the 
scandal had caused a loss of faith in the tibetan 
administration he forbade unofficial contacts with taiwan and 
established a committee to investigate previous dealings 
we are wasting the best opportunity we ever had within these 30 
years on minor issues he said 
at risk are gains made since the awarding of the prize focused 
attention on tibet where chinese troops have killed scores of 
proindependence activists in the past two years lhasa tibets 
capital had been under martial law for 13 months when it was lifted 
may 1 
there also is concern that the conservative faction might try to 
take advantage of the disunity and get the dalai lamas concessions 
to china retracted which would scuttle dreams of an early return to 
tibet 
in a 1988 speech the dalai lama said he was willing to give 
china control over tibets foreign affairs and defense in exchange 
for autonomy in internal matters 
the dalai lama recently fired several top officials including 
his representative in tokyo in an attempt to end the crisis he 
dissolved the cabinet and instituted reforms designed to open the 
exile government to public scrutiny 
voting by 368 tibetan representatives from around the world may 
14 in dharmsala filled only three of the seven cabinet seats at 
least nine candidates dropped out and some representatives handed in 
empty ballots to express opposition to the reforms 
</TEXT>
