<TEXT>
wuer kaixi is haunted by thoughts that he may have 
enticed people to their deaths in central beijing a year ago 
on the evening of june 3 1989 as chinese troops prepared their 
bloody assault to clear tiananmen square of the prodemocracy 
protesters who had occupied it for three weeks wuer appealed to 
the people of beijing for help 
as night fell i thought there werent enough people on the 
square that it was becoming more and more dangerous he recalled 
in an interview exactly one year later 
thinking that numbers would protect the students he rushed about 
the capital for more than four hours that night holding rallies and 
urging people to flock to tiananmen chinas symbolic political 
center 
many people went he said looking back i feel very its 
so difficult to say but i believe many people heard me speak went 
to tiananmen square and were killed 
hundreds of unarmed civilians were killed when soldiers rammed 
their way through beijings streets with tanks to recapture 
tiananmen wuer who collapsed from exhaustion and left the square 
in an ambulance shortly before the soldiers arrived says at least 
3000 died 
wuer was born in beijing and lived there for 16 years before 
attending high school in xinjiang the region in chinas far west 
largely populated by wuers fellow ethnic uygurs 
his proper name is uerkesh daolet wuer kaixi is the chinese 
transliteration of his first name 
it was during his first year back in beijing in a prefreshman 
preparatory course at beijing normal university in 1988 that wuer 
made a name for himself as a cocky but articulate thinker who was 
quick to question authority 
he became head of a confucian study group that started out as a 
forum to discuss his major education but quickly developed into an 
arena for political debate 
i was outspoken i was a headache for the administration a 
troublemaker he says 
he was a troublemaker even to his friends who were trying to slip 
him out of the country after june 4 
i didnt want to leave friends spent a lot of time not so much 
helping me leave china but convincing me to go he recalls 
so many times i said so what if i get caught i get caught 
now however i understand them said wuer now 22 
he left china at the end of june by means he declined to 
describe in detail his name was no 1 on the governments wanted 
list which ensured media attention overseas and within a few weeks 
he was made vice chairman of the fledgling federation for a 
democratic china headquartered in paris 
he scoffs at reports that he embezzled money or is a womanizer 
what bothers me is when the communist partys peoples daily 
says im disliked he says i have lots of friends 
he travels widely and has been invited by the sakharov committee 
in the soviet union to attend a human rights seminar in moscow this 
weekend 
but his top priority remains political reform from within the 
chinese system we have some branch organizations inside china 
even in the army and the most important thing for us is to send 
information to china just hold on and wait for an opportunity that 
opportunity will probably be the death of the old man senior leader 
deng xiaoping 
wuer says the death of deng 85 could trigger new 
demonstrations but he said change will be slow fifty or 100 
years later then probably china will become a democratic china 
on monday the first anniversary of the crackdown on the 
prodemocracy movement wuer stood with a group of chinese 
dissidents across from the chinese embassy in paris chastising 
embassy officials for refusing to see them 
all we wanted to do was deliver a letter seeking a dialogue we 
just tried to tell them we still want to go back to china and that 
were not criminals he said 
but they are afraid of us they are afraid of popular peoples 
power thats the truth 
</TEXT>
