<DOCNO> AP900605-0024 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
in a sign of the cold wars thaw officials say 
the united states may lend the soviet union a technological hand to 
destroy thousands of tons of chemical weapons 
as recently as three years ago the soviets had not acknowledged 
having any such weapons 
an agreement signed by president bush and soviet president 
mikhail s gorbachev last friday requires both sides to begin 
destroying their arsenals of deadly gases by 1992 questions remain 
though about how the soviets will carry it out 
the kremlin decided last summer to bow to pressure from domestic 
environmentalists and close a new plant built to destroy chemical 
weapons by incineration the soviets have disclosed no plans for 
building another plant and it remains unclear how they will meet the 
1992 date set in the new agreement 
barry daniel chief spokesman for the arms control and 
disarmament agency which oversaw negotiation of the agreement said 
monday he could not rule out the possibility that the united states 
might agree to destroy the soviets chemicals for them 
he said this carried large legal risks however and it appeared 
more likely that the united states might offer to help build or 
operate a plant on soviet soil 
the bushgorbachev agreement requires the two sides to cooperate 
in developing safe and environmentally sound methods of destroying 
their chemical stockpiles both sides are to have no more than 5000 
tons of weapons by the year 2002 compared with 25000 tons now held 
by the united states and 50000 tons by the soviets 
the united states plans to begin destroying some of its older 
chemical weapons on johnston atoll in the pacific late this year 
well ahead of the schedule set in the chemical agreement daniel 
said 
the johnston atoll plant was built to meet a congressional 
requirement set in 1985 to destroy all existing us chemical 
weapons by 1997 as a condition for approving a pentagon program to 
produce a new generation of chemical arms 
plans call for building other destruction plants at existing 
chemical arms stockpile sites in oregon utah colorado arkansas 
alabama kentucky indiana and maryland 
elisa harris a chemical weapons expert at the brookings 
institution a washington think tank said ussoviet collaboration 
on technical aspects of chemical arms destruction would help moscow 
overcome domestic environmental critics 
they would like to have the american stamp of approval on their 
technology to persuade the critics that destruction can be 
accomplished safely she said 
in recognition of the technical and environmental obstacles 
facing both the united states and the soviet union the new 
agreement gives each side until 1999 to destroy 50 percent of the 
chemicals covered by the accord the remaining amounts would be 
destroyed in the final three years of the agreement 
the soviet procedure for destroying chemical weapons is to 
decompose the active nerve agent by mixing it with alcohol making 
it nontoxic it then is burned the us method skips the 
decomposition step and burns the chemicals in an incinerator that 
heats the agents to 2700 degrees fahrenheit 
the chemicals mainly nerve agents and mustard gases are used in 
a variety of artillery projectiles mortar cartridges land mines 
rockets and gravity bombs 
the use of chemical weapons is outlawed by the 1925 geneva 
protocol signed by 149 nations but there are no international 
limits on possession or production 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

