<TEXT>
americans are cutting down on fatty and 
highcholesterol foods but 61 percent still are overweight 
according to a national survey 
there is no evidence that americans are winning the battle of 
the bulge says a report by prevention magazine based on an annual 
poll conducted by louis harris and associates 
the proportion of adults who are overweight has remained close to 
60 percent since 1983 when the magazine began commissioning the 
polls 
levels of regular strenuous exercise have also remained about the 
same over the past seven years about 35 percent in the latest 
survey said they work up a sweat for at least 20 minutes at least 
three times a week 
the survey of 1250 adults was conducted by telephone nov 6 
through dec 13 last year no margin of error was given 
among the bright spots in preventions report card were continued 
reductions in the number of people eating foods high in fat and 
cholesterol 
half of those polled said they try a lot to avoid eating 
highcholesterol foods like eggs dairy products and fatty meats 
up from 42 percent in 1983 
and 58 percent said they avoid eating too much fat up from 55 
percent in 1983 and 54 percent in 1988 
the evidence is overwhelming that a diet high in fat is a 
major threat to health and longevity and it appears that the public 
is getting that message the magazines report said 
but the survey also found a decline in efforts to get enough 
vitamins and minerals down five percentage points from 1983 to 58 
percent and to avoid sugary foods also down five points from the 
first survey to 46 percent 
among those who are overweight more than half are at least 10 
percent over the recommended weight range for their height and 
build a quarter were within their recommended range and 15 percent 
were underweight 
about 35 percent said they exercise strenuously at least three 
times a week by sex that was 42 percent of the men and 29 percent 
of the women 
the survey found that men were more likely to exercise 
strenuously and frequently while women were found to be more 
nutritionconscious 
the survey also found 
46 percent of respondents said they avoided sugar compared with 
51 percent in 1983 
eating fish twice a week followed the same trend down from 34 
percent in 1985 the first year the question was asked to 28 
percent in the latest poll 
53 percent said they have their cholesterol level checked at 
least once a year 
44 percent of women said they examine their breasts to check for 
possible cancer at least once a month down from 51 percent in 1988 
but up from 37 percent in the first survey 
75 percent have a dental exam at least once a year 
28 percent said they smoked cigarettes down from 30 percent in 
1983 
questions about alcohol and drug use found 91 percent drink 
moderately or not at all and 94 percent never use recreational 
drugs such as marijuana speed and downers 
