chinese thai and american officials joined attempts 
tuesday to foster progress in peace talks that were stalled on the 
brink of signing a ceasefire in cambodias 11year civil war 
japanese officials said 
thai and cambodian officials said a meeting would be held later 
in the day but it was still not clear whether all four contending 
parties would be present or whether a ceasefire would emerge 
the first session of the talks broke off monday after just 25 
minutes because the khmer rouge the strongest guerrilla group 
opposing the hanoibacked government in phnom penh refused to 
attend without the right to raise issues and sign the truce pact as 
an equal partner 
a flurry of diplomatic activity focused on the 16th floor of the 
imperial hotel where prince norodom sihanouk and other members of 
his threeparty guerrilla coalition including the khmer rouge 
were staying in rooms along one corridor 
chinese ambassador yang zhenya was seen leaving the corridor a 
japanese foreign ministry official speaking on condition of 
anonymity said a us diplomat had visited the guerrilla 
delegations earlier tuesday the americans identity was not 
immediately known 
thailands deputy prime minister gen chavalit yongchaiyudh a 
key drafter of the proposed ceasefire left the corridor with two 
highranking japanese foreign ministry officials 
it appeared progress was in the air as chavalit replied 
positively when asked if the cambodians had accepted a proposal but 
he left without giving further details 
the peace conference the first in japan since world war ii 
appeared to have collapsed monday when the khmer rouge nominal 
leader khieu samphan boycotted the opening session 
but informal meetings continued mostly in the hotel where the 
guerrilla delegations were staying pressure came from other 
countries including china which backs the khmer rouge the united 
states which backs sihanouk while trying to distance itself from 
the khmer rouges harsh and even genocidal reputation and thailand 
through which arms flow to the rebels 
all four of cambodias warring factions had tentatively agreed to 
a ceasefire before coming to tokyo but the hardline communist 
khmer rouge refused to participate in twosided peace talks between 
the loose guerrilla coalition and the government of premier hun sen 
hun sen has refused to negotiate equally with the khmer rouge or 
allow them an equal role in a future interim government saying that 
might allow them to return to power 
hundreds of thousands of cambodians died during the groups 
197579 brutal rule before vietnam invaded in late 1978 and 
installed the moderate communist hun sen government 
vietnam says it withdrew all its troops in september but there 
are charges that some remain in cambodia 
if a truce were signed it would be the first time the sides 
actually had signed a ceasefire but the draft agreement lacks any 
mechanism to police a truce even if a ceasefire is worked out the 
sides disagree on measures to administer the country before 
elections can be held 
sihanouk who once was king of cambodia has led the 
threefaction guerrilla coalition since 1982 he believes the 
faction must be included in any political arrangement for the 
country saying its disciplined and powerful army would be the best 
guarantee against a return of the vietnamese 
in bangkok sihanouk spokesman roland eng said heavy fighting was 
continuing and guerrilla groups had launched offensives in areas 
around phnom penh cambodias capital 
we are still carrying on normally on the battlefield nobody 
knows what will happen in tokyo so for the time being we will 
continue as normally on the battlefield he said monday 
