<TEXT>
when is a ussoviet treaty not a treaty when 
its an agreement a convention a protocol a contract a joint 
statement or a memorandum of understanding 
does it make any difference it does to members of congress 
thousands of other officials and hundreds of millions of people 
worldwide who may be affected 
president bush and soviet president mikhail s gorbachev signed a 
trade agreement often called a treaty though it is not a treaty in 
the strict sense the constitution requires that a treaty be 
approved by twothirds of the senate ever since the senate rejected 
the treaty of versailles at the end of world war i presidents have 
preferred to use simpler executive agreements 
these are put into effect much more easily 
charles maechling a former state department official estimated 
that about 60 treaties which had to take that form are awaiting 
ratification in the senate now sometimes when the president sees 
possible trouble ahead he does not even ask the senate to approve a 
treaty president carter held back the strategic arms limitation 
treaty after soviet troops invaded afghanistan in 1979 
countries with parliamentary systems do not have this kind of 
complication when their executives make major decisions their 
legislators either approve or face the threat of a new election 
congress has required that they review trade agreements if they 
are made with countries that have been under communist rule it was 
busy this week ironing out a constitutional difficulty on the 
procedure such agreements need a simple majority vote in both 
houses 
bush has said he would wait to send congress the agreement with 
the soviets until the supreme soviet has passed a new law allowing 
all its citizens to emigrate more freely 
other accords not subject to the same law often are sent to 
congress anyway influential members might be offended if they were 
not when members of congress are insulted they may hold back the 
funds to carry out agreements 
the executive pretty well has to flash them by congress said 
maechling who has worked on many pacts 
he is now a visiting scholar at the brookings institution a 
private study group on public policy 
an accord between bush and gorbachev on chemical weapons was 
designed to give a push to a pact that will bring a ban by as many 
governments as are willing to sign president sadaq hussein of iraq 
emphasized the importance of that in april when he threatened to 
make the fire eat half of israel chemical weapons are much 
cheaper and easier for third world countries to make than nuclear 
weapons 
the ban will be called a convention which maechling said was 
just a treaty under another name one official suggested that the 
word convention may sound less forbidding but usually calls for 
the same action by the senate as a treaty does 
some accords get negotiated far down the bureaucratic line by 
lowerlevel officials and may not go before congress at all 
back in the 1970s when henry kissinger was secretary of state 
and he was trying to negotiate detente with the soviet union 
somebody he never heard of the chairman of the maritime 
commission i think negotiated an agreement on shipping with the 
soviets maechling said 
kissinger was furious he only found out about it when the 
agreement worked its way up through the bureaucracy 
this time it was announced during gorbachevs visit that 
secretary of state james a baker iii or other officials had 
negotiated among a long series of accords one that opens 42 ports 
in this country and 42 in the soviet union 
the us negotiator was warren g leback a former merchant ship 
captain who holds the title of maritime administrator 
