kari gellers struggle against crippling 
illness has taught her to savor the simple joys that other 
teenagers often overlook the wonder of a blade of grass sunlight 
glinting on the surf a mothers inexhaustible love 
the story of 18yearold miss gellers fight to overcome a 
devastating muscle ailment is told in her first achievement as a 
budding playwright a oneact drama that premiered monday at the 
kennedy center 
the play titled the waiting was one of three winners of the 
1990 young playwrights award from very special arts a nonprofit 
educational affiliate of the kennedy center which provides arts 
programs for the mentally and physically handicapped 
a central figure in miss gellers highly personal play is based 
on her mother karla geller 50 who relived her childhood bout with 
polio when her daughter was stricken with encephalitis a viral 
infection of the brain at the age of 15 
she was an incredible help to me said miss geller a high 
school senior in san clemente calif she was such a role model 
she showed me that i was not alone she didnt once let me know she 
was scared she was so strong throughout that she made me strong 
miss gellers ailment formally known as postencephalitic 
muscular dystonia involved a gradual constriction of her muscles 
that left her hands clenched tightly her neck immobilized and her 
feet bowed and twisted inward 
after three years of painful physical therapy that included 
horseback riding to improve her balance and coordination miss 
gellers handicap is barely noticeable today she walks with leg 
braces and has regained the use of the thumb and forefinger on each 
hand 
she says she hardly notices either unless she tries something 
like piano playing 
i dont let it get in my way she said after receiving her 
award from jean kennedy smith founder of very special arts and a 
hug from sabrina le beauf a star of the cosby show 
miss geller a member of the laguna playhouse youth theater 
plans to enter the california institute of the arts in valencia this 
fall to pursue a drama career 
she said her illness deepened her affection for her mother a 
special education teacher in los angeles who still walks on crutches 
weve always been best friends the daughter said shes 
the most important person in my life its amazing how many things 
we shared the spinal taps the therapy the hospital nurses when i 
wrote the play we sat down and talked for hours about her feelings 
and the events of the past 
her illness taught her to appreciate life more and not to take 
things for granted miss geller said 
i remember the first time i got out of the house she said 
mother and i got salads and went down to the harbor and sat on the 
grass i watched the water sparkling and looked at a blade of grass 
and saw how beautiful it was i appreciated those things finally 
