an influential house republican says hell tell 
the white house that heads ought to be rolling at the maritime 
administration for its maintenance of a rusting cargo fleet that 
would be activated in a national emergency 
rep william s broomfield of michigan told maritime officials 
monday that the national defense reserve fleets ships were 
glorified rust buckets and a waste of money 
broomfield expressed his annoyance after the governments top 
maritime executive and a senior navy official defended the fleet at 
a hearing of the house small business subcommittee on regulation 
business opportunities and energy 
broomfield is the ranking republican on the subcommittee but 
more importantly serves as the senior gop member of the house 
foreign affairs committee 
the fleet consists of 331 mostly mothballed vessels including 
72 world war iiera victory ships the maritime administration 
is spending 67 million this fiscal year to provide minimal 
maintenance for the oldest part of the fleet and 89 million for the 
newer 96ship ready reserve portion the agency is requesting 225 
million for the ready reserve in fiscal 1991 
i agree that the outward appearance of many reserve ships is 
poor to a visitor maritime administrator warren g leback 
testified 
but the transportation department official said the working 
machinery is protected by dehumidification the hulls are treated to 
slow deterioration and the ships would be able to sail again as 
they did when last called to service during the vietnam war 
rep ron wyden dore chairman of the subcommittee joined 
broomfield in protesting lebacks upbeat assessment and both 
lawmakers said they would sponsor legislation to have the ships sold 
to us salvage companies 
i wouldnt want to serve on one testified navy cmdr john 
polley who criticized the state of the fleet last year in an 
investigation he conducted for the defense department inspector 
generals office 
broomfield said lebacks defense of the fleet when the cold 
war seems to be ending and the nation faces a staggering budget 
deficit convinces him that heads ought to be rolling at the 
maritime administration he vowed to get to the white house with 
his complaint 
wyden said the taxpayers are getting repeatedly fleeced 
for these maritime cadavers he accused the maritime 
administration of running a subsidy program for foreign salvage 
companies because ships leaving the fleet went to overseas scrap 
yards 
jonathan d kaskin director of the navys strategic sealift 
division told the subcommittee that the pentagon considers the 
fleet a strategic asset because modern container ships cannot carry 
tanks howitzers and other heavy equipment 
he said the navy wants to build the ready reserve to 142 ships by 
1994 but in the meantime must rely on the world war iiera vessels 
because until we get something better this is all weve got 
youre living in nevernever land wyden said 
a recent associated press inspection of some ships in the fleet 
berthed in the james river at fort eustis va revealed rusted and 
broken railings paint peeling all along the exterior and even 
anklehigh grass growing through wooden deck boards 
below decks were mattresses on metal bunk beds dusty lockers 
old mess halls crankstyle telephones huge ovens and steel cooking 
pots 
the 96 vessels in the ready reserve part of the fleet are 
designated to sail on five to 20 days notice an additional 42 are 
so old they will be used as target practice for navy gunners sunk 
to become reefs or traded to salvage companies for newer ships the 
remaining ships are supposed to be seaworthy on 30 to 120 days 
notice 
except for the ready reserve which is spread out across the 
country the reserve fleet is located at fort eustis near norfolk 
at beaumont texas and in suisun bay near san francisco 
leback said the maritime administration was forced to sell its 
disposable ships to foreign rather than us scrap yards because the 
agency has a responsibility to obtain the highest possible return 
on these government assets 
he testified and us salvage industry officials agreed that 
the domestic industry cannot outbid foreign firms because of 
environmental and workplace safety regulations imposed on american 
firms 
the industry representatives said us companies would bid on the 
jobs if a law were passed to require that the work go to domestic 
concerns 
