the united states doesnt need a super rocket 
and can rely on its fleet of expendable launch vehicles through the 
end of the century a defense department advisory panel says 
instead of building a heavylift booster the defense science 
board said the military should push two technical approaches that 
hold promise for breakthroughs in rocket technology the 
airbreathing propulsion being developed for the national aerospace 
plane and nuclear engines 
although launching rockets incorporating nuclear devices 
presents emotional and political difficulties the task force review 
leads us to recommend continued investment in this area said the 
report released monday 
the boards finding would in effect leave the soviet union 
unchallenged in heavylift capacity its energia is the worlds most 
powerful rocket capable of putting a 220000pound cargo into low 
earth orbit 
the most powerful cargo carrier used by the united states is the 
space shuttle which can lift 52000 pounds into orbit the biggest 
expendable rocket the titan 4 can carry a 39000pound payload 
in the apollo moon landing program of the late 1960s and early 
1970s the united states used saturn 5 rockets capable of lifting 
310000 pounds of cargo but the assembly lines were shut down when 
that program ended 
the science board said it was uncomfortable with a 1987 national 
security directive signed by president reagan that called for 
development of a heavylift launch vehicle for the antimissile 
strategic defense initiative 
