<TEXT>
president bush is likely to block new offshore 
oil activity along the california and florida coasts while calling 
for environmental impact studies administration officials say 
the longpending decision would ease republican electionyear 
concerns in the environmentally conscious states if bushs decision 
follows the officials expectations 
however white house press secretary marlin fitzwater said today 
that bush has not decided this issue yet and he ruled out the 
possibility of an announcement this week 
the option bush is said to be leaning to would bar new drilling 
off florida until the year 2002 off northern california until 1997 
and off southern california until at least 1992 according to 
officials who spoke monday on condition of anonymity 
the dates reflect the years when the governments fiveyear 
leasing plans are up for review the current one expires in 1992 
the officials cautioned that the president still could change his 
apparent course and open the way for some drilling but they said 
that appeared unlikely 
a task force bush appointed last year to study effects of 
potential drilling in the three areas concluded that there was not 
enough information to go ahead with the new offshore activity 
the florida congressional delegation has unanimously urged bush 
to bar offshore drilling as has republican gov bob martinez who 
is seeking reelection to a second term 
republican sen pete wilson seeking the governorship of 
california wants a total ban on new oil activity along the coast 
and opposed the reagan administrations efforts to expand leasing 
areas 
a postponement would fall short of the decision sought by 
environmentalists who contend there have been enough studies to 
show the environmental harm and warrant a permanent ban in both 
states 
the public has moved far beyond where delays are going to 
satisfy people its time to move to protect some of these areas 
permanently said lisa speer an attorney for the natural 
resources defense council 
the broadest set of options initially drawn by the presidents 
staff ranged from opening the study areas for leasing and drilling 
to permanently banning such activity 
bush has expressed the most interest in options involving 
postponement of new oil activity pending new studies and more 
specific options were developed accordingly the officials said 
the president named a task force last year headed by interior 
secretary manuel lujan to work with the national academy of 
sciences in studying the environmental impact of opening the three 
areas to oil leasing 
the regions under consideration are a 67million acre section 
of ocean off southern california 12 million acres off northern 
california and 13 million acres in the gulf of mexico near the 
florida everglades 
a policy initiated by former president reagans interior 
secretary james watt opened the entire 14billionacre outer 
continental shelf but leasing has been blocked over the years by 
congressionally imposed moratoriums 
in florida the government sold 73 leases in the affected area in 
the early 1980s for 108 million the cost of buying the leases back 
could be closer to 200 million interior department officials say 
southern california is the only region of the country other than 
the gulf of mexico where offshore oil development is under way 22 
oil platforms are operating 
the interior departments current fiveyear program had 
anticipated new lease sales last september but they were put off 
pending bushs decision 
the northern california leases about 90 miles north of san 
francisco and off eureka had been scheduled for sale early last 
year but the sale was postponed 
