the soviet legislature today tentatively postponed 
until september adoption of a new emigration law that washington 
says is necessary before it will give moscow preferential trade 
status 
president mikhail s gorbachev and president bush signed a trade 
agreement at the washington summit but bush said he wont press the 
us congress to grant the soviet union mostfavorednation trading 
status until the emigration legislation is passed 
soviet restrictions on emigration have for decades been a major 
impediment to improved ussoviet relations millions of dollars of 
trade and the fate of soviets hoping to emigrate are riding on 
approval of the law 
the soviet legislature by acclamation adopted a new agenda that 
dropped consideration of the emigration law before the body adjourns 
june 14 for the summer 
fyodor burlatsky a member of the legislatures international 
affairs committee had said in a television interview recently the 
law would be considered may 31 
the decision drew immediate criticism from lawmakers who said it 
opened the soviet union to accusations of duplicity 
we will turn out to be cheats we wont be trusted they will 
say well they made a promise and again the soviet union is 
deceiving nikolai medvedev a supreme soviet member from 
lithuania told the session 
in response supreme soviet chairman anatoly lukyanov held out 
the possibility that the decision would be reviewed and the law 
taken up earlier 
the president will arrive we will look it over and if there is 
a possibility we will include this issue we will look it over with 
the president lukyanov said 
it was not clear whether the postponement was made with 
gorbachevs approval whether it was a mistake or whether other 
kremlin leaders engineered the decision it could be an 
embarrassment to gorbachev who was returning from the summit today 
lukyanov is a close ally of gorbachev carrying out the leaders 
will in the legislature and he did not explain why he allowed what 
appeared to be such a radical shift so soon after the soviet 
commitment in washington to enact the legislation 
medvedev said soviet officials had promised us senators during 
the justcompleted summit that the new emigration bill would be 
approved during the current supreme soviet session 
the proposed legislation which was given preliminary approval in 
november would allow emigration of virtually anyone who has entry 
permission from another country and no outstanding alimony 
obligations criminal charges or recent knowledge of state secrets 
