<TEXT>
a federal judge has ruled that top elected 
officials in the nations most populous county systematically 
discriminated against hispanic voters to protect their own positions 
in office 
the plaintiffs called mondays ruling a landmark civil rights 
decision that will end more than a century of white domination of 
politics in the county of 87 million people an estimated 35 
percent are hispanic but no member of any minority group has been 
elected to the board of supervisors since 1875 
the ruling by us district judge david kenyon charged that los 
angeles countys fivemember board conspired to protect their 
incumbencies and that of their allies when they redrew the 
countys five voting districts in 1981 
the judge said the redistricting violated the 1965 federal voting 
rights act and the equal protection clause of the 14th amendment to 
the constitution 
the decision immediately throws the results of todays balloting 
in two supervisorial districts into question plaintiffs urged that 
the results be thrown out and kenyon said he would hold a hearing 
thursday to determine how the election results should be handled 
for 115 years the los angeles county board of supervisors has 
been an exclusive male allwhite club said marc rosenbaum an 
attorney for the american civil liberties union foundation of 
southern california which was one of the plaintiffs today that 
club membership is open to everyone 
attorney general dick thornburgh called the ruling a victory 
against discrimination the justice department had joined in the 
suit 
representatives of the mexican american legal defense and 
educational fund another plaintiff said they would demand that 
county officials immediately redraw boundaries and create a largely 
hispanic district 
we want a remedy now we want a remedy that encompasses a fair 
opportunity for our community to represent itself and to elect 
representatives who will represent its interests said antonia 
hernandez president and general counsel for the legal fund 
disputing the countys claims that creating a hispanicmajority 
district was impossible kenyon found that the hispanic community 
was large and geographically compact such that a fivedistrict 
plan can be drawn in which hispanics comprise a majority of the 
citizen votingage population in one of the five districts 
kenyon also recommended expansion of the board saying the 
districts are too large for one person to represent constituents 
adequately 
supervisor kenneth hahn said he will introduce a motion at 
tuesdays meeting to expand the board to seven members such 
proposals have been introduced before and would be subject to voter 
approval 
pete schabarum a supervisor who decided not to seek reelection 
said the timing of kenyons ruling confused elections 
i continue to believe that district lines should not be based 
on ethnic factors he added 
supervisor michael antonovich predicted the county would appeal 
county counsel dewitt clinton would not comment on that possibility 
the lawsuit filed in august 1988 charged that the supervisors 
deliberately spread the countys hispanic population across several 
districts when they redrew voting boundaries following the 1980 
federal census 
the explosive and continuous growth of the los angeles county 
hispanic community was evident at the time of the adoption of the 
1981 redistricting plan as was the steady decline of the countys 
nonhispanic white population kenyon wrote 
the judge also concluded that hispanics and nonhispanics are 
widely polarized when it comes to voting trends hispanics vote in 
large numbers for fellow hispanics he said and nonhispanics 
rarely vote for hispanics 
attorneys for both sides have said they believe the judge will 
allow the supervisors to redraw district boundaries which he could 
accept or reject 
</TEXT>
