<TEXT>
new jerseys supreme court today declared 
the states 15yearold system of financing public schools 
unconstitutional because it hurts poorer urban school districts 
in the unanimous ruling the court said the system left such 
districts without the money and resources they need to give their 
children the education that the state constitution requires 
the dilemma is that while we spend so much there is absolutely 
no question that we are failing to provide students in the poorer 
urban districts with the kind of education that anyone can call 
thorough and efficient said the ruling which was written by 
chief justice robert n wilentz 
the justices ordered lawmakers to begin fixing the problem by the 
199192 school year they said the state must assure that 
disadvantaged districts spend about the same amount of money on each 
child that is spent in richer suburban districts 
the court estimated it would have added about 440 million to the 
35 billion the state spent this year on public school aid to boost 
funding in poor districts to the required levels 
it said more money is particularly needed to meet the special 
education needs and address the extreme disadvantages of 
schoolchildren in poor communities 
the court said it is not ordering equalized financing statewide 
richer districts may choose to spend more on education but the 
state would be required to increase its aid to poorer districts if 
the education in those school systems continues to be lacking 
lawmakers may devise any remedy they wish to correct the 
disparities between wealthy and poor districts but they may not do 
it by forcing poor districts to raise property taxes the court 
ruled 
capping a decadelong legal battle the justices repeatedly said 
education financing cannot depend on the decisions of local schools 
boards and districts must be guaranteed a certain amount of money 
every year 
they also rejected the states argument that money will not solve 
the problem because many urban districts will simply mismanage and 
waste the additional money 
money can make a difference if effectively used it can provide 
the students with an equal educational opportunity a chance to 
succeed they are entitled to that chance constitutionally 
entitled wilentz wrote 
new jersey is among more than a dozen states where courts have 
overturned school finance systems in recent years the others are 
texas kentucky kansas wisconsin california connecticut 
washington west virginia wyoming arkansas and montana 
the latest conflict pitted the state against the newarkbased 
education law center the center which brought the lawsuit in 1981 
charged that new jerseys 35 billion system discriminates against 
poor districts because of its heavy reliance on property taxes 
it contended that poor and urban districts are unable to raise 
the money needed to provide a quality education and that the system 
has allowed the gap between rich and poor districts to widen 
the lawsuit was brought on behalf of 20 schoolage children from 
four new jersey cities 
after a similar legal battle fought throughout the 1970s the 
court ordered the legislature to overhaul new jerseys school 
financing system and lawmakers enacted a state income tax to pay 
for more state education aid in todays decision the court found 
that those reforms did not fully solve the problem 
its a victory for the schoolchildren of new jersey and the 
courts proposed remedy strives to do essentially but in a more 
modest way what the governor has proposed himself said emma 
byrne gov jim florios spokeswoman 
this latest ruling comes barely a week after florio unveiled a 
sweeping plan to overhaul the financing system 
the governor wants to spend more state money on poor and 
middleincome districts and reduce or eliminate aid to wealthier 
school systems he also wants to increase the income tax to provide 
1 billion more in state education aid 
his plan establishes a minimum amount of money that districts 
should spend on each child and determines how much the community 
should be required to raise on its own based on property wealth and 
the wealth of a communitys residents the state would then provide 
aid to make up the difference 
in 1988 administrative law judge steven lefelt ruled that the 
financing system as reformed in the 1970s had failed because 
poorer districts still fell behind wealthier districts 
i do not believe in fixing what is not broken however 
plaintiffs have proven the system is broken he said in his ruling 
he said more money may not be the only solution but that it is a 
start 
administrative law decisions are subject to review by state 
officials education commissioner saul cooperman rejected lefelts 
findings agreeing with the stand that then gov thomas h keans 
administration took for the eight years it fought the lawsuit 
</TEXT>
