<TEXT>
if jim wright has any regrets about 
resigning as house speaker hes not saying so and they arent 
showing 
he looks tanned and relaxed in his fort worth office which is 
cluttered by papers and memorabilia from 34 years in congress along 
with notes for the book he is writing on central america 
wright says he hasnt been happier in years and talks without 
bitterness about his resignation a year ago during an ethics 
investigation 
i have a sort of predestinarians view of things almost a 
religious conviction that things happen for the better and i just 
accept it that way wright said in a recent interview 
wright delivered his resignation speech to the house on may 31 
1989 six days later he officially gave up the post he had held for 
about two years he left congress on june 30 
he stepped down after the house ethics committee said wright 
violated house rules 69 times involving sales of his book 
reflections of a public man and in business deals with his 
friend george mallick of fort worth 
wright maintains the charges were false and brought by his 
enemies he insists that he never knowingly violated house rules he 
said events leading to his resignation fell together to create 
this jigsaw puzzle out of which there was no escape 
but wright said his fall from power did allow him an escape of 
sorts hes now free to do things that were impossible in 
washington such as having dinner with his wife betty and spending 
time with his children and grandchildren 
the 67yearold wright still works long days writing giving 
speeches or guest lectures at colleges and appearing at 
fundraisers for fellow democrats he recently attended a gathering 
for his replacement pete geren who often consults wright for 
advice 
an avid gardener wright spent a recent weekend planting 52 rose 
bushes in his back yard and had a few sore muscles 
im happy im as busy as i want to be and im not nearly as 
busy as i used to be im very glad im not he said during my 
last 12 years in congress i was running to catch up it was a 
constant choice between most urgent and merely urgent and the 
simply important never got done 
wrights study in his new threebedroom home contains few signs 
of his tenure in washington which he says at times was 
oppressive hectic harried harassing 
he refuses to criticize his successor speaker tom foley or the 
house except to say its not moving with any discernible clarity 
or purpose 
he still believes actions by his nemesis republican rep newt 
gingrich and special prosecutor richard phelan amounted to 
character assassination 
and wright blames the media for a voracious thirst for 
scandal he says reporters didnt give him a chance to tell his 
side 
during the past year mallick went to bankruptcy court and 
liquidated the company that was under house investigation 
mrs wright whose job with the company mallightco was 
questioned by the ethics committee is less circumspect than her 
husband in assessing the investigation 
i think that it leaves scars i dont think theres any way to 
get away from it she said 
wright said he sometimes yearns to be involved when he sees 
reports about such things as the crumbling of the berlin wall or 
soviet leader mikhail gorbachevs visit to the united states 
but there are other people who can do those things i had my 
chance i had 34 years and thats plenty i did everything i could 
do and the best i could do he said 
