<TEXT>
the soviet legislature on tuesday tentatively 
postponed adoption of a law to ease restrictions on emigration 
possibly jeopardizing a summit deal that would vastly increase trade 
with the united states 
president mikhail s gorbachev signed the trade agreement during 
this weeks washington summit with president bush bushs only 
condition for implementing the trade agreement was that the soviet 
legislature give final approval to the longawaited emigration law 
but the supreme soviet on tuesday approved an agenda that does 
not include consideration of the law in its current session which 
ends june 14 the supreme soviet does not convene again until 
september 
the proposed law would permit emigration for virtually anyone who 
has entry permission from another country and no outstanding 
obligations criminal charges or recent knowledge of state secrets 
it would set a basic limit of five years on the length of time a 
citizen can be kept from emigrating because of access to secrets 
there was no explanation for the decision to omit the item from 
the agenda and legislators held out the possibility it could still 
be added during the current session 
we will look it over and if there is a possibility we will 
include this issue we will look it over with the president said 
anatoly lukyanov the chairman of the legislatures executive 
committee gorbachev returned to moscow on tuesday 
reform has allowed lawmakers to criticize the leadership but 
gorbachev and lukyanov his close ally almost without exception 
have managed to bend the legislature to their will 
it was not clear whether postponement of the law was made with 
gorbachevs approval whether it was a mistake or whether other 
kremlin leaders engineered the decision possibly to embarrass the 
absent leader 
the unexpected step could signal that gorbachev intends to make 
good on his warning that he might curtail jewish emigration if 
israel continues to settle emigres in occupied territory 
jewish activists in moscow issued a statement tuesday protesting 
the threat which gorbachev made at a news conference in washington 
on sunday 
soviet authorities have no moral or legal right to dictate to a 
sovereign government where jews who have lost their soviet 
citizenship should live said the statement read over the 
telephone by spokesman oleg nesterov 
the statement called the threat one of a series of attempts to 
use jews as an object of trade in a political game 
another possible reason for the delay might be that the soviets 
are not prepared to handle the number of people wanting to emigrate 
and the demands they will place on transport and visa workers 
the government may also be hesitating because an embarassingly 
high number of people could choose to leave their country 
passage of the emigration law would affect an unknown number of 
soviets including jews and other ethnic groups without it the 
soviet union will not have access to million dollars in trade with 
the united states under the summit agreement 
the decision to delay consideration angered some soviet lawmakers 
we will turn out to be cheats we wont be trusted they will 
say well they made a promise and again the soviet union is 
deceiving said nikolai medvedev a legislator from lithuania he 
said soviet officials had promised us senators during the summit 
that the new emigration law would be approved before the legislative 
session ends this month 
fyodor burlatsky a member of the legislatures international 
affairs committee said in a television interview recently the law 
would be considered may 31 
the law passed on its first reading in november but final action 
has been delayed repeatedly by crises over other economic and 
political reforms 
referring to potential lost trade with the united states supreme 
soviet member igor griazin of estonia said there are fairly 
serious economic consequences to not adopting the law on entry and 
exit 
rudolf a kuznetsov head of the visaissuing agency uvir has 
predicted 5 million to 6 million of the 287 million soviets would 
emigrate or travel abroad this year 
last month alone soviet authorities issued about 20000 exit 
visas 
the bill under consideration would codify many changes that have 
already been put into practice here for example procedures 
required to obtain travel documents and permission to emigrate have 
been eased tremendously in the last two years 
soviet officials acknowledge that the main obstacles to travel 
have become the heavy workloads of emigration authorities shortages 
of plane and train tickets and problems with currency exchange 
currently soviet citizens are allowed to exchange about 300 when 
they go abroad on a guest or tourist visa and this puts a strain on 
the financially strapped soviet union 
