<TEXT>
the proposed soviet emigration law would allow 
emigration for virtually anyone who has permission to enter another 
country and no outstanding obligations criminal charges or recent 
knowledge of state secrets in the soviet union 
it would also set a basic limit of five years on the length of 
time a citizen can be kept from emigrating because of access to 
secrets 
complete details of the proposal are not known but the bill 
which was given preliminary approval by the supreme soviet in 
november codifies many changes already put into practice in the 
soviet union 
the procedures required to obtain travel documents and permission 
to emigrate have already been eased a great deal in the last two 
years releasing a flood of visitors and emigrants across the soviet 
borders 
soviet officials acknowledge that the main obstacles to travel 
have become the heavy workloads of emigration authorities shortages 
of plane and train tickets and problems with currency exchange 
the financially strapped country can ill afford to allocate hard 
currency for citizens to spend abroad officials say now soviet 
citizens are allowed to exchange rubles for about 300 when they go 
abroad on a guest or tourist visa 
before the current liberalization of travel regulations tens of 
thousands of jews and other soviets were refused exit visas 
becoming known as refuseniks their plight brought repeated 
censure from the west 
because there has been no legal limit on how long a person could 
be denied exit on the grounds he knew state secrets there have been 
cases of refuseniks being denied visas for up to 20 years 
activists say there are still dozens if not hundreds of 
refuseniks held because of state secrets or because relatives have 
refused to sign papers giving them permission to leave 
but most former refuseniks have left and less than 1 percent of 
applications to emigrate are currently being turned down according 
to visa officials 
