<TEXT>
federal safety officials on tuesday blamed a 
shifting river channel for the 1989 collapse of a tennessee highway 
bridge that killed eight motorists but investigators said state 
officials should have corrected the problem a decade ago 
the national transportation safety board expressing concern 
about thousands of other bridges throughout the country also cited 
the 54yearold structures simple design as a contributing factor 
in the april 1 1989 collapse the bridge carried the two 
northbound lanes of us 51 over the hatchie river 45 miles north 
of memphis 
the board cited the tennessee department of transportation for 
failing to evaluate and correct problems found in inspections dating 
back to 1979 the river channel has moved 83 feet since the bridge 
was constructed in 1936 investigators said 
the board voted 31 on the probable cause and 40 on a set of 
recommendations to federal and state officials board member jim 
burnett said he would not support the conclusion until further 
inspection after missing bridge parts are recovered 
the boards investigation remains open said chairman james 
kolstad and could be revised if evidence surfaces that points to 
further deficiencies in the bridge investigators told the board 
that bridge parts might be raised from the water in about two weeks 
kolstad said tennessee officials need to improve their 
inspections and maintenance procedures they recognized the problem 
but they did not evaluate it they did not take action to correct 
the situation kolstad said 
he said recent flooding in the south increases the danger of 
bridges being undermined 
im concerned that some of these bridges may be put back into 
service without adequate inspection kolstad said 
the board said it was unlikely that a fracture in any of the 
concrete columns of the tennessee bridge triggered the collapse 
it said the bridge failed most likely from the deterioration 
of timber piles that were originally buried and not designed to be 
in water the fact that the piles were improperly exposed to the 
river channel was known as early as 1979 inspectors said 
the ntsb staff also had blamed the accident partly on 
construction of an adjacent bridge in 1974 to carry us 51s 
southbound lanes which their draft report said accelerated the 
shift in the river channel but the board said the collapse would 
have occurred eventually even without the new bridge and deleted 
the southbound bridge as a contributing factor 
the final report said however enough information and guidance 
was available for the designers of the southbound bridge to have 
discovered the natural channel meander of the hatchie river and to 
have anticipated that further migration would undermine the 
northbound bridge 
the report said the drivers of passenger cars and trucks on the 
bridge had no way of avoiding the accident it also said emergency 
crews could have done nothing more to reduce its severity 
board members also cautioned tennessee authorities against 
allowing so many exemptions to vehicle weight restrictions on 
bridges about 70 a month for the hatchie bridge before it 
collapsed and called for closer scrutiny of overweight trucks and 
their impact on bridge safety 
</TEXT>
