<TEXT>
it was another stunning public relations 
triumph for mikhail s gorbachev abroad he won a trade deal some 
bank credits and new friends in business 
but gorbachevs weeklong visit to north america yielded no quick 
fix for the soviet economy and wont translate soon into tangible 
improvements in the lives of a frustrated and angry soviet people 
changing a system means changing people intelligent people 
gorbachev told business executives in minnesota its not just 
some kind of layout that you see on a piece of paper and you can 
just tear up that piece of paper a system is people people who 
live people who have their own interests who have their own 
lives 
he acknowldged also that people are afraid of change which he 
said is why the first five years of perestroika have had such 
limited results 
referring to his signing of a new trade pact with president bush 
in washington gorbachev said the agreement to establish normal 
trade ties is of great political importance 
but he said it will not have much practical effect right now 
for the period of transition to a market economy 
whats more bush made very clear during the summit last week 
that he will not send the trade agreement to congress for approval 
until the soviet union passes a new emigration law liberalizing 
restrictions on soviet citizens who wish to leave the country 
the supreme soviet legislature tuesday put off further 
consideration of the emigration bill at least until its next 
session which begins in september and even if gorbachev gets the 
issue back on the calendar us congressional leaders have said 
they intend to tie passage of the trade bill to settlement of the 
lithuanian crisis an even thornier dispute over the baltic 
republics declaration of independence from soviet rule 
during gorbachevs overnight stop in ottawa at the start of his 
trip across north america canada agreed to extend a 500 million 
line of credit to the soviet union over the next two years to help 
the soviets purchase canadian technology and consumer goods 
but last year when the soviets decided to spend substantial 
hardcurrency reserves to buy consumer goods abroad in order to show 
the soviet people some tangible benefits of reform the 
transportation system broke down and trainloads of such 
hardtofind items as toothpaste and laundry soap stacked up on the 
border because there was no place to unload them 
now in a classic demonstration of the failure of central 
planning the logjam has broken and a glut of imported detergent is 
stacked on otherwise empty store shelves 
gorbachev repeatedly mentioned during his trip the signing of an 
agreement with chevron corp to help explore and develop the vast 
tengiz oil field in a joint venture with the soviet government the 
field is believed to contain more than twice the petroleum reserves 
of alaskas great prudhoe bay 
but chevron officials having already learned the difficulties of 
doing business with the soviet union in a much smaller and less 
ambitious project say they expect long and complicated negotiations 
before any work begins 
and it will be years before the soviet economy or the american 
oil company begins to reap any reward 
a central theme of gorbachevs visit was that he wants to improve 
the climate in the soviet union for western business he not only 
encouraged captains of industry to invest their capital in his 
country and cited concessions his government has made to encourage 
them he warned that if they dont move now their reluctance will 
be remembered later 
youre wondering could involvement with the soviet union become 
a trap could you lose money as a result gorbachev said seeking 
to reassure them he said risk is good both in politics and 
business but adventurism is bad in both 
the current soviet leadership is in favor of profound changes 
but still it fully intends to do that in a careful way he said 
the soviet president reminded americans that market systems have 
been evolving in western countries for centuries and he is trying 
to put one in place practically overnight 
he could offer no guarantee that the troubled climate will clear 
anytime soon 
the reforms already introduced have so upset the old system he 
said our ship has lost anchor and therefore were all a little 
sick 
