an environmental adviser to president bush said 
tuesday that the nation has made remarkable progress in improving 
the environment over the past two decades but we have a long long 
way to go 
michael deland chairman of the presidents council on 
environmental quality said the next major strides in improving the 
environment will depend on industries voluntarily preventing 
pollution because doing so is in their economic interest 
the government should not walk away from ensuring that industry 
complies with environmental laws deland told reporters but he 
added that pollution prevention will not happen by federal or any 
other level of government fiat 
instead industries and businesses will find ways to reduce 
pollution because it will be economically beneficial to do so said 
deland a former regional administrator for the environmental 
protection agency 
deland made his remarks in releasing the council on environmental 
qualitys annual report which this year reviewed environmental 
progress made over the last 20 years 
the 494page report which the government sells for 17 provides 
a generally upbeat review of the countrys environmental record 
since 1970 the document suggested that while environmental problems 
persist remarkable improvements have been made in some areas 
such as overall air quality 
it noted however that progress in dealing with pollution in 
major cities and the protection of wetlands and coastal waters has 
come slowly 
the summary did not deal significantly with such concerns as 
global warming and the destruction of the ozone layer by manmade 
pollution which are relatively new areas of environmental concern 
deland whose appointment to the presidents council was hailed 
by environmentalists said a review of the last 20 years show the 
time has been largely a period of success 
