the judge in the mcmartin preschool 
molestation case on tuesday refused to dismiss any of the charges in 
defendant raymond buckeys retrial saying there was no double 
jeopardy 
superior court judge stanley weisberg acknowledged that some 
testimony may not have matched exactly the charges against him but 
he said the accounts by three young girls provided sufficient 
evidence to justify continuing the trial 
defense arguments concerning inconsistencies in testimony can be 
made to the jury when the case is submitted for decision the judge 
said 
under the constitution people cannot be subjected to double 
jeopardy being tried a second time on charges for which they wre 
found innocent but people can be tried a second time if there is a 
mistrial rather than an acquittal 
buckeys attorney danny davis argued that the counts on which 
buckey was being retried must be presented in the same way as they 
were in the first trial or it isnt really a retrial but a 
completely distinct and novel trial proceeding 
he sought dismissal of five of the eight counts by arguing the 
testimony didnt match the allegations detailed in the charges 
but the judge said i dont find there is a double jeopardy 
problem i find this is an erroneous analysis of double jeopardy 
in the case of one child who testified davis said the 
prosecution alleged she was molested while seated on buckeys lap 
during a horsey game on the stand the child said buckey was 
lying prone on the floor and she was on top of him she denied she 
was seated on his lap 
another child specifically denied being raped and sodomized with 
a foreign object davis noted although she alleged other acts of 
molestation the other acts are not specified in the charges 
the 32yearold buckey is being retried on eight molestation 
charges unresolved by the jury at his first trial the longest and 
costliest criminal case in us history 
the first buckey trial ended in january with buckey acquitted of 
40 counts of molestation and his mother acquitted of 12 charges but 
the jury deadlocked on 13 counts against buckey and the district 
attorney decided to retry him on eight of those charges involving 
three girls now 12 and 13 years old 
