<TEXT>
sen richard lugar ranking republican on the 
senate agriculture committee said tuesday he would not compromise 
with the democrats to raise target prices and loan rates in the 1990 
farm bill 
he also said he was not willing to take more acreage out of 
production or accept shifts in finances to create the illusion of 
deficit reduction without real cuts 
ive been infinitely flexible in other things in the bill 
he said but he said these four areas were not negotiable and would 
lead to a floor fight if the democratic majority on the committee 
insists in keeping them in the bill 
the democrats have to decide do we want an issue or do we 
want a bill said lugar if an issue is what they want then my 
guess is we will have a oneyear extension 
congress passes a farm bill every five years to set agriculture 
policy including the degree to which the federal government will 
subsidize farmers through target prices and loan rates 
current law expires in december but the bush administration has 
said repeatedly that it would accept a oneyear extension of 
existing policies 
that is viewed by many in congress as a strategy that would help 
us negotiators at international trade talks at which the united 
states is trying to get other countries to remove subsidies from 
agricultural products that distort world market prices 
agriculture secretary clayton yeutter who is actively involved 
in those talks has said that us subsidies may have to be adjusted 
to comply with whatever agreement develops 
lugar mentioned the trade talks in a session with reporters but 
said his main objection to the democrats proposal for increasing 
target prices is budgetary 
at a time when it is fairly likely people may be asked to pay 
more taxes for the farm program to be asking for more money is not 
prudent he said 
lugar said however he did not know for sure if a tax increase 
was going to be proposed by president bush or congressional leaders 
who are discussing solutions to the governments spending problems 
lugars comments preceded a meeting of a senate agriculture 
committee task force that is trying to compromise the republican and 
democratic proposals on price supports 
the democrats want to increase target prices 1 percent with other 
increases possible in the last four years of the program depending 
on inflation 
the house agriculture committee meanwhile has voted to freeze 
target prices 
