<TEXT>
new jersey is failing miserably at educating 
poor urban students the state supreme court ruled tuesday in a 
decision that declared unconstitutional the way aid is distributed 
to public schools 
the high court ruled in effect that determining school funding 
based on property tax revenues is unfair 
the evidence compels but one conclusion the poorer the 
district and the greater its need the less the money available and 
the worse the education chief justice robert n wilentz wrote 
these students simply cannot possibly enter the same market or 
the same society as their peers educated in wealthier districts 
the justices in the unanimous decision ordered lawmakers to begin 
reforms by the 199192 school year 
the state must assure poor urban districts spend about the same 
amount of money per child as richer suburban districts the court 
ruled 
the court estimated that the state needs to add 440 million to 
its 35 billion public schools budget to remedy disparities in the 
states 28 poorest districts 
todays ruling is a clear victory for the children of new 
jersey said gov jim florio who last week unveiled a plan to 
raise the state income tax the tax hike would raise 1 billion for 
more aid to middleincome and poor districts while aid to wealthier 
school systems would be reduced or eliminated 
the court has recognized that the current school funding system 
is leading us to be two new jerseys where some youngsters head for 
the best colleges and others go down a road to nowhere florio 
said predicting his reform proposal will satisfy the court 
new jersey is among more than a dozen states where courts have 
overturned school finance systems in recent years 
i think there absolutely is a trend evident in the last two 
years we have seen four state supreme courts strike down their 
school finance systems montana kentucky texas and now new 
jersey said arthur wise director of the washingtonbased rand 
center for the study of the teaching profession 
other states involved in funding disputes include kansas 
wisconsin california connecticut washington west virginia 
wyoming and arkansas 
since 1980 the gap between rich districts and poor districts 
has been increasing thats why we have this trend the poor are 
more hardpressed than they were during the 1970s wise said 
a new school funding system will take effect in montana on july 
1 passed by lawmakers after the states highest court declared the 
former system unconstitutional 
in october the texas supreme court declared its system 
unconstitutional the state senate on tuesday approved and sent to 
the house a 528 million education reform bill 
a funding bill that would hike sales taxes by a quartercent and 
increase taxes on mixed drinks and tobbacco products was passed by 
both the texas house and senate on tuesday 
the kentucky supreme court delivered a similar ruling last year 
forcing lawmakers to raise taxes to pay for 500 million more in 
education aid 
the new jersey decision does not place a cap on spending and rich 
districts can continue to increase spending if they choose but the 
state must increase aid to poorer districts if subpar education 
standards continue the court said 
lawmakers may devise any remedy they wish to correct the 
disparities but they may not force poor districts to raise property 
taxes the court ruled 
the court also ruled unconstitutional the politically popular 
minimum aid program that gives money to affluent districts 
regardless of need 
the rulings stem from a 1981 lawsuit filed by the newarkbased 
education law center which brought the court action on behalf of 20 
schoolage children from camden jersey city east orange and 
irvington 
the ruling culminated a decadelong battle during which former 
gov thomas h kean fought the lawsuit and defended the funding 
system 
in 1984 the court said school districts spent an average of 
4030 per pupil while the poorest school systems spent only about 
2860 per pupil statewide an average of 3329 per pupil was 
spent 
