<TEXT>
an alldigital allamerican highdefinition 
television system developed by a us company has made a lastminute 
entry in the race to become the us national tv broadcast standard 
officials said tuesday 
we are leapfrogging stateofthe art technology said mike 
walker a spokesman for the videocipher division of general 
instruments corp showcasing the new digicipher technology in 
san diego 
highdefinition tv or hdtv provides vastly sharper tv pictures 
and compact discquality sound however its signal requires a wider 
broadcast channel about 30 megahertz rather than conventional 
tvs 6 megahertz 
the federal communications commission set a june 1 deadline for 
proposals on a simulcast system that works on todays tv sets 
and fits onto the existing broadcast spectrum on june 1 general 
instruments filed its proposal 
the technologies that weve developed are proprietary 
technologies that digitize and compress the video signal walker 
said we reduce the amount or data that is transmitted but 
maintain or enhance the quality of the picture 
conventional tvs would receive the standard signal while the 
second signal would be broadcast and received on hdtv equipment 
whose manufacturers pay lucrative royalties to the owners of the 
technology 
other proposals before the fcc are from nhk the japanese 
broadcasting system zenith electronics corp an international 
consortium of nbc with dutch and french electronics companies and 
massachusetts institute of technology 
the systems would be tested for 12 to 18 months before the 
government chooses the standard sometime in 1993 
walker said the technology grew out of videocipher research for 
its core market satellite and cable systems into a digital 
compression system that would let multiple tv signals move through a 
single satellite relay 
it is a seamless technology walker said the same system of 
coding compression and decoding can be used by satellite and cable 
systems as well as terrestrial tv broadcasting 
the videocipher division of general instruments which is 263rd 
on the fortune 500 specializes in satellite encryption systems 
plans to have its hdtv prototype system before the fcc in february 
1991 
walker said the digital system will have the advantages of error 
correction circuitry already familiar to compact disc owners 
electronic noise snow interference and ghost images would 
canceled out 
you can send that signal through noise take it out of 
correction and wind up with a perfect signal an exact duplicate of 
what was transmitted he said 
the digital compression technology will increase the number of 
signals handled by a single satellite relay or transponder walker 
said 
we could send two highdefinition signals on one transponder 
or we could send up to 10 highquality standard signals to a 
single transponder he said the same technique would apply to a 
cable channel or a broadcast signal 
the company plans to develop the compression technology for 
overseas markets he said lowering costs for satellite time and 
increasing available channels 
ultimately what were looking for is video on demand the 
video store in the sky walker said you can see the day where 
therell be 10 movies on 10 channels on 10 transponders 24 hours a 
day 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

