reorganization as a smaller carrier servicing even fewer routes 
especially to small communities than before the strike 
i would see it as a very positive kind of move said jim 
cammisa publisher of travel industry indicators in miami 
prior to the strike they were marginally profitable on an income 
basis theres no reason with their ridership up to 75 or 80 
percent why they cant pass a breakeven profit level fairly soon 
others said the reorganization could help greyhound raise badly 
needed working capital but would delay the companys attempted 225 
million junk bond buyback 
the chapter 11 filing buys time for greyhound at the start of the 
busy summer travel season but may force it to sell assets and 
jettison bus routes said phua k young a shearson lehman hutton 
analyst in new york 
serving a lot of smaller communities im afraid has gone the 
way of the dinosaurs a lot of momandpop bus operators out there 
are just waiting to see what lines that greyhound wants to get rid 
of he said thats where the future lies for regional 
carriers 
