<TEXT>
the british will get less for their money wednesday 
as a new smaller five pound note enters circulation engraved with a 
gracefully aging queen 
the new fiver the first in two decades is designed to combat 
hightechnology forgeries and cut production costs 
no item created by man cant be recreated said nigel 
bevittsmith manager of design and development at the bank of 
englands printing works what we try to do is to make it 
timeconsuming and as expensive as possible 
the dominant blue of the older note has been lightened from navy 
to turquoise and a blend of background colors was created to 
challenge sophisticated forgers who use modern color reproduction 
machines 
the position and color of the numbers has also been changed to 
foil counterfeiters and a silvercolored thread runs through the 
new note as it already does in 10 20 and 50 pound notes 
the bank of england which has already printed 200 million of the 
new notes said queen elizabeths new portrait shows the monarch 
gracefully aged the older fivepound note portrays the queen as 
a young delicate brunette 
railway pioneer george stephenson replaces the duke of wellington 
on the new notes which have been slightly reduced in size 
the fiver also contain a round turquoise symbol to make them more 
easily identifiable to the partially blind 
all english notes will be redesigned over the next four years and 
will be 16 percent to 22 percent small the bank of england said 
bevittsmith said the bank will save a few million pounds 
from the size reduction 
