<TEXT>
the soviet union said tuesday it plans 
to withdraw a very substantive part of its nuclear arsenal from 
central europe this year 
the soviet foreign minister eduard a shevardnadze told a 
35nation conference on human rights the soviets will cut 1500 
nuclear warheads by the end of the year from central europe 
in addition 60 tactical missile launchers and 3200 artillery 
guns capable of firing nuclear shells would be cut he said 
secretary of state james a baker iii in copenhagen for the 
conference said the western allies welcomed the announcement and 
added the soviets have quite an advantage in these weapons 
but he said it was unclear how many such tactical weapons the 
soviets had previously intended to withdraw and whether they would 
be destroyed or redeployed 
shevardnadze said of the reduction this is going to be a very 
substantive amount he said relatively few weapons would remain 
but he refused to be more specific 
asked if the weapons would be destroyed shevardnadze said 
its our intention to withdraw the weapons and discuss destruction 
at a subsequent phase 
in his speech to the conference on security and cooperation in 
europe shevardnadze said that by freeing europe of nuclear 
weapons we give further latitude to man 
european foreign ministers responded carefully to the soviet 
plan citing the soviet superiority in shortrange weaponry 
we have to look at this in detail said roland dumas of 
france adding anything that goes in the direction of disarmament 
is a good initiative 
hansdietrich genscher of west germany told reporters after 
meeting privately with baker we first have to know what is behind 
this idea of the soviets he said he would await the details 
danish foreign minister uffe ellemannjensen said his first 
impression was that theres not much new in the proposal 
disarmament is likely to be a top item at the agenda of another 
conference on security and cooperation in europe meeting in paris in 
december the csce is comprised of the united states canada and all 
european states except albania 
dumas told reporters the paris summit would probably be held dec 
1921 to discuss the reconciliation of europe a preparatory 
meeting was called for july 10 in vienna 
genscher said after meeting shevardnadze that there was a broad 
understanding the vienna talks on conventional weapons which had 
slowed in recent months should be concluded before the paris 
meeting 
shevardnadze also held out hope of a compromise on the military 
future of a united germany which the west wants to see as a full 
member of the nato alliance 
nato and the sovietled warsaw pact alliance were undergoing a 
process of transformation and starting to cooperate in this way 
we can find a compromise on the german issue he said 
baker was carrying a package of proposals to present to 
shevardnadze that are designed to overcome soviet reluctance to let 
germany stay in nato 
presidents george bush and mikhail s gorbachev failed to resolve 
differences over the issue during their washington summit over the 
weekend 
bakers proposal includes an offer of help by west germany to 
build housing for soviet soldiers returning home from eastern 
europe and other economic inducements 
it also includes reassurances that a larger and stronger germany 
would not threaten the soviet union move beyond its present borders 
or acquire nuclear or chemical weapons us officials said 
the copenhagen meeting granted observer status to albania in a 
further sign that europes last hardline communist state wants to 
end its isolation 
an application by lithuania to attend as an observer was 
rejected however denmarks ellemannjensen said no consensus was 
possible since the soviets would object to seating a separate 
lithuanian delegation the baltic republic declared itself 
independent from the soviet union in march and the kremlin has 
imposed economic sanctions in an effort to end the independence 
drive 
