<TEXT>
the sharp firstquarter decline in us 
productivity or production efficiency was centered almost entirely 
in the service sector and that makes the bad news even worse 
the reason in terms of employment the american economy is 
overwhelmingly a service economy meaning most people earn their 
living from jobs in the serviceproducing realm rather than the 
manufacture of goods 
rather than making nuts and bolts they use their skills to 
provide transportation communication power wholesale and retail 
trade banking real estate insurance health care research 
government services 
statistically speaking it is a little known world even by 
government which is one of the largest segments of that world 
washington releases masses of information about goods much less 
about the world of services 
popular impressions are even hazier most people have mental 
pictures of mining manufacturing and construction but they have no 
clear image of services as an industry something promised never 
delivered they might say 
yet three of four us workers are employed in the economys 
service or serviceproducing sector and most future employment 
growth for the next decade is likely to be in those areas 
moreover much of that growth is likely to be concentrated in 
just three service areas retail trade personal services such as 
health care and education and state and local government 
no wonder economists are appalled at firstquarter figures 
showing a 27 percent drop in productivity or output per hour 
worked they know that if productivity doesnt rise neither can 
living standards its that simple 
it shows in various others ways too most importantly in regard 
to global competition a nation that cannot efficiently join ideas 
and raw materials with manpower and money to produce goods and 
services cannot compete 
and it has a direct link to inflation most clearly seen in 
higher labor costs to produce results those higher costs of 
course necessitate higher prices which in turn force higher wage 
demands 
it is no coincidence for example that as productivity gains 
shrank over the past three decades some of the highest inflation 
and interest rates in a century burned the economy and helped bring 
on deep recessions 
those high interest rates in turn helped raise the cost of 
doing business and thereby contributed to the very productivity 
problem that led to them in the first place 
moreover those same high interest rates discouraged investment 
in more modern stateofthe art plants and equipment in a better 
educated work force in innovative computerenhanced measures all 
aimed at greater productivity 
lagging productivity is therefore a summary term for a whole 
basket of maladies that afflict the economy and end up in the cost 
of goods and services 
that long list certainly includes poor education high capital 
costs lack of innovation waste in health care political 
chicanery high legal expenses government overspending 
environmental abuse shortsighted management improper economic 
policies unmotivated workers lack of access to capital 
you might add to that list the misdirection of capital such as 
in the investment of billions of dollars in junk bonds and corporate 
takeovers in recent years instead of improvement of production 
techniques and worker education 
all these raise the costs of producing goods and services and 
thereby reduce production efficiency when production efficiency 
falls so does the ability to compete 
and if you dont compete these days you dont live very well 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

