<DOCNO> AP900605-0183 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
like the mighty mississippi in his signature 
song ol man river william warfield plans to keep rollin along 
his bassbaritone is still rich with musical thunder though 40 
springs have come and gone since he first became a national star 
singing the moving anthem about the hard life of black stevedores 
working on the mississippi river in the mgm movie show boat 
hes 70 now still on the road captivating audiences here and 
abroad and still sharing his art and wisdom with eager fans and 
students since 1974 hes taught at the champaignurbana campus of 
the university of illinois and his retirement from the music 
faculty is merely a technicality 
ill still teach but ill be able to do more outside things 
said warfield thumbing through a calendar in his small office in 
smith hall im booked up with performances through next may 
during his 54year career the versatile singer and pianist has 
run the gamut of show business from stints in churchs and 
nightclubs that merely paid the rent to performances on stage and 
screen 
the son of a baptist preacher his goal as a student at the 
eastman school of music at the university of rochester was not to 
see his name in lights but to teach 
i didnt have stars in my eyes and i wasnt sure you could make 
a living by singing said warfield in an interview it never 
occurred to me that i would be that lucky 
as luck would have it warfield joined the 1946 touring company 
of call me mister a broadway musical revue about soldiers 
getting out of the army after world war ii and their adjustment to 
civilian life he was bitten by the performance bug he appeared 
on stage with other future stars comedian buddy hackett 
comedianwriterdirector carl reiner and 
choreographerdancerdirector robert fosse 
i decided to stick around new york and try to make a career for 
myself said warfield 
his big break came in 1950 a canadian stockbroker attended 
nearly every one of warfields shows in a toronto nightclub and 
offered 500 to finance his concert debut at new yorks town hall 
the critics gave rave reviews to warfield whose oneman recital 
ranged from handel to experimental music with hymns spirtuals and 
blues 
my attitude was that id get a manager and make a living not 
that id become a star he said he did not realize the impact of 
his performance until the the reviews hit the street 
the saturday review said warfield had remarkable presence and 
range and the heraldtribune said he had a wideranged 
flexible and sumptuous voice newsweek called him one of the 
brightest stars to appear in music in years 
whew warfield recalled everything broke loose 
while performing at the invitation of the australian broadcasting 
commission warfields manager larney goodkind signed him to play 
joe the dockhand in the mgm version of show boat it was a role 
first created by stepin fetchit in 1929 and paul robeson in 1936 
it was during the early days of production that warfield 
delivered his famous onetake recording of ol man river 
intended as a dryrun with the orchestra to give warfield an idea of 
timing and balance it was flawless it reportedly brought tears to 
the eyes of the head of the studio louis mayer 
i had been singing ol man river since high school said 
warfield it never occurred to me that i would be singing it in a 
movie 
warfields career was in high gear and in 1952 he performed in 
porgy and bess during a tour of europe sponsored by the us 
state department he played opposite the opera star leontyne price 
they soon were married but the demands of two separate professional 
careers left them little time together they divorced in 1972 
in 1975 warfield gave a soldout concert in carnegie hall 
marking the 25th anniversary of his new york debut 
but his gifted baritone was not limited to singing he appeared 
as de lawd in the green pastures a 1957 hallmark hall of fame 
television production in 1984 he received a grammy award for his 
narration of aaron coplands a lincoln portrait 
bob bays a retired music educator said warfield is superb as 
both performer and teacher he is one of our major artists he has 
a truly magnificant voice with that wonderful warm quality that 
communicates with people 
it was in 1974 that a friend at the university of illinois 
suggested warfield for a faculty position though he never had been 
to the campus his friends recommendation and the reputation of the 
universitys music school brought him to the university to teach 
i kept my career active i wasnt giving up performing just 
adding something said warfield who scheduled classes midweek so 
he could tour and perform its been a matter of organization 
one of his students was opera star jerry hadley who studied 
oratorio with warfield in the 1970s 
i got to know him very well said hadley he told those of 
us in his first class to call him uncle bill and thats what we 
always called him 
bays said warfield always was close to his students and provided 
a role model for young black musicians more black students than 
well ever know got through the university because of bills support 
and concern said bays 
warfield was born in west helena ark the eldest of five sons 
his father moved the family to rochester ny where warfield grew 
up loving music 
he sang in the church choir as a boy soprano then studied piano 
but it was his high school music teacher who recognized his 
potential as he matured and his voice changed she encouraged him to 
enter a national music competition he won a scholarship to eastman 
where eventually he earned both a bachelors and a masters degree 
little will change when warfield officially retires from the 
university in august he will give up without much regret 
administratives chores and chairmanship of the voice program but he 
still will perform and teach 
and students likely will continue to drop into his home for 
advice and sometimes a slice of the sweet potato pie for which 
uncle bill is famous 
i love to cook thats my relaxation when im home warfield 
said and there are always a lot of students around to use as 
guinea pigs 
</TEXT>
