<TEXT>
here is a chronology of events leading up to mondays filing for 
protection from creditors under chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy 
code by greyhound lines inc 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
march 19 1987 an investor group led by fred g currey acquires 
the bus operations of greyhound corp since renamed greyhound dial 
corp and takes them private in a 270 million leveraged buyout 
july 14 1987 the new greyhound lines inc pays 80 million for 
dallasbased trailways lines inc then the nations largest 
operator of trailways buses 
march 2 1990 most of the companys 6300 bus drivers go on 
strike over wages and job security two shots are fired into 
greyhounds main chicago terminal but there are no injuries it is 
the first of scores of shootings bomb threats and incidents 
vandalism reported by the company 
march 3 a picketing driver in redding calif is killed after 
being crushed by a bus driven by a replacement driver 
march 18 greyhound walks out of contract negotiations in 
tucson ariz to protest strike violence and says it wont resume 
talks until a week passes without violence 
march 31 the driver of an independent bus operating on a 
greyhound route from nashville tenn to louisville ky under a 
pooling arrangement is shot and critically wounded by a man in a 
passing pickup 
april 12 using new hires and drivers who cross picket lines 
greyhound says it is serving 72 percent of prestrike miles the 
union dismisses the claim 
may 3 the company says it is serving 87 percent of prestrike 
locations and passenger loads are just over half of the previous 
years levels 
may 4 greyhound reports a 558 million firstquarter loss and 
blames it partly on increased expenses to cope with strike violence 
may 5 in the first talks in six weeks greyhound offers 
contract that would cut 4500 union jobs change from permile wage 
rates to hourly wage rates and freeze wages for four years union 
calls offer an insult no further talks are scheduled 
may 7 currey declares victory saying strike has become 
irrevelant because company has hired enough drivers to replace 
strikers 
may 21 the company asks holders of 225 million of its junk 
bonds to sell them back at steep discounts to help it avoid 
bankruptcy it also changes its pay scale for drivers and withdraws 
proposed bonus and pension schemes to save money 
may 23 two striking employees are sentenced to jail in boston 
for damaging buses the first jail terms handed down for 
strikerelated violence 
may 29 a financial adviser hired by drivers requests a meeting 
with greyhound to discuss a possible employee buyout 
june 4 greyhound files for protection from creditors under 
chapter 11 of the us bankruptcy code 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

