<TEXT>
the merger of british insurance broker willis 
faber plc and new yorkbased corroon amp black corp will help both 
companies expand into new markets in continental europe and the 
pacific rim officials said 
the companies also said the deal would give each broker access to 
the others home market where they currently have little presence 
we have a perfect fit and the synergies will come immediately 
i believe said richard miller chairman and chief executive of 
corroon amp black 
willis faber and corroon amp black said monday they had agreed on a 
778 million stock swap that would create the worlds fourthlargest 
insurance broker the brokers link insurance underwriters with a 
broad range of clients including airlines shippers and 
manufacturers 
top executives of the two companies already are planning to shop 
for other firms in europe and the pacific to fulfill their expansion 
aims 
well be working europe together very soon miller said 
were starting to make joint efforts to attract some new players 
to this team 
its definitely a drawback if you do not have the resources in 
place where your customers have offices miller said spreading 
out internationally makes you more competitive definetely 
you have to be able to take care of your clients wherever they 
are said john vh robins executive director of willis faber 
britains secondlargest insurance broker after sedgwick group plc 
the new firm willis corroon plc would be based in britain and 
is expected to have 1990 revenue of about 1 billion the merger 
would create the worlds fourth largest insurance brokerage in terms 
of revenue marsh amp mclennan cos inc of new york is the largest 
news of the merger did not cheer investors though willis faber 
shares dropped nearly 9 percent to 265 pence the equivalent of 
443 a share on the london stock exchange corroon amp black fell 
225 to 3425 a share on the new york stock exchange 
corroon amp black stockholders would get 78 willis faber shares 
for every corroon amp black share they hold the equivalent of 3455 
a share based on mondays closing price the deal values corroon amp 
black at the equivalent of 778 million 
despite the lackluster market reaction some analysts praised the 
strategy behind the deal 
i think that some of the best opportunities for 1992 are for 
the brokers who can easily cross international lines said gloria 
vogel a stock analyst at bear stearns referring to the scheduled 
dismantling of trade barriers within europes common market 
the new company would be 60 percentowned by shareholders of the 
british group and 40 percentowned by corroon shareholders the 
companies said 
miller would be chief executive of the merged firm roger j 
elliott chairman of willis faber would be executive chairman of 
the new company 
the board of willis corroon is to have equal representation from 
the two companies 
the merger is expected to be completed by the end of september 
the proposed transaction must be approved by stockholders of both 
companies and by us and british regulators 
neither company forsaw much employee overlap in the merged 
business 
corroon amp black is the worlds sixthlargest insurance brokerage 
it also provides risk management advice reinsurance brokerage and 
other services such as health care and employee benefits 
willis faber the worlds fifthlargest brokerage handles 
insurance and reinsurance brokerage as well as risk management 
services its serves clients in the fields of aviation marine and 
energy 
corroon has nearly all its business in the united states while 
willis faber gets about 80 percent of its revenues from britain 
corroon sold its 299 percent interest in the british broker minet 
holdings plc in february 1988 
willis fabers aftertax profit rose 19 percent to 376 million 
pounds or 63 million in 1989 on a 4 percent revenue gain to 2378 
million pounds or 397 million 
new yorkbased corroon amp black however has suffered from its 
exposure to the depressed us insurance market for the first 
quarter the company reported a 29 percent decline in net income to 
91 million as revenue fell 4 percent to 117 million 
</TEXT>
