<TEXT>
officials from the united states and 16 of its 
allies will meet wednesday to discuss the easing of controls on 
hightechnology exports to eastern bloc countries 
formed in 1949 at the start of the cold war the coordinating 
committee for multilateral export controls has served as a watchdog 
agency limiting the shipment of strategic technology to warsaw pact 
nations 
known as cocom the committee is made up of all nato member 
counties except iceland plus japan and australia 
at the twoday meeting officials of the 17 countries are 
expected to approve a relaxation of controls on exports of 
telecommunications equipment computers and machine tools 
in the past the united states has been more reluctant than most 
of the other members to ease controls but at a cocom executive 
committee meeting in february following the developments in 
eastern europe us officials said they would support total or 
partial relaxations of curbs on more than 40 of the 120 regulated 
technology categories 
one new issue facing cocom is the likelihood of rapid german 
unification west germany is expected to outline its plans for 
dealing with the question of hightechnology transfers between east 
germany and the soviet union which are major trading partners 
</TEXT>
