ernest saunders the former chairman of guinness 
plc took the witness stand tuesday as the defense began its case in 
the first of two trials resulting from the giant brewers 1986 
takeover of distillers co 
saunders lawyer richard ferguson described his client as the 
victim in britains largest whitecollar scandal he said the 
prosecutions case against saunders was weak and attempted to 
substitute quantity for quality 
the jury trial which began feb 16 entered its 63rd day 
tuesday saunders and six other defendants are accused of being 
involved in a scheme to arrange for the purchase of guinness stock 
during the takeover fight for distillers a scotch whisky and gin 
maker 
the aim of the alleged conspiracy was to boost the price of 
guinness stock and thus make the companys 42 billion cash and 
stock bid more attractive than a rival offer from supermarket 
operator argyll group plc 
the takeover succeeded in april 1986 but in december of that 
year the department of trade and industry announced it was 
investigating and the alleged financial wrongdoings became public 
the imperative of course is to find a scapegoat ferguson 
told the court something has gone wrong with this great company 
someone has to carry the can 
ferguson said saunders who had to obtain legal aid to cover his 
huge legal fees was testifying voluntarily under british law he 
is not required to give evidence on his own behalf 
i could say to you that whatever happens he is a ruined man 
stripped of the means of earning his livelihood his personal life 
in ruins and himself undermined cast aside we would say by the 
company he served loyally for five years ferguson said 
but he still has something to fight for and that is his 
credibility 
saunders wearing a navyblue doublebreasted suit began his 
evidence by giving details of treatment he was having for two 
medical complaints a hernia and a thyroid gland problem he said he 
has separated from his wife and she has moved abroad 
standing trial with the 54yearold saunders are gerald ronson 
51 chairman of heron international plc former stockbroker anthony 
parnes 44 and millionaire financier sir jack lyons 74 
they face a total of 35 charges including stock manipulation 
theft false accounting and destroying documents 
saunders faces two charges of conspiring to contravene the 
prevention of fraud investments act two charges of authorizing or 
permitting guinness to contravene the companies act eight charges 
of false accounting two charges of theft and one charge of 
destroying company documents 
in the second trial scheduled to begin sometime after october 
