<DOCNO> AP900605-0213 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
coors brewing co has forged a deal with stroh 
brewery co to purchase strohs memphis tenn facility an 
aquisition marking the first time coors will make beer outside of 
golden co officials said tuesday 
the companies said they hoped to complete the transaction by july 
3 but stroh said it would operate the 500employee breery until 
sept 1 the brewery sale price was not disclosed 
this purchase is part of our overall strategy to position coors 
brewing co for future growth said peter coors president of 
goldenbased coors brewing it will provide the additional 
capacity we need to respond to rising consumer demand for our 
products 
coors brewing co earlier reported shipping a record 39 million 
barrels of beer during the first quarter of this year when it also 
reported record net sales of 394 million the memphis brewery with 
an annual brewing capacity of 55 million barrels will increase 
coors annual production by nearly a third 
adolph coors co the parent company of coors brewing founded in 
1873 by german immigrant adolph coors this year surpassed 
detroitbased stroh as the nations no 3 brewer with a 9 percent 
market share 
anheuserbusch with its 42 percent share and miller brewing co 
with its 22 percent share were the top brewers 
coors last year produced 177 million barrels of beer the 
company ships some to its satellite packaging facility in elkton 
va which has a packaging capacity of 25 million barrels 
the announcement comes less than a week after anheuserbusch 
accused coors of engaging in false and deceptive advertising by 
implying that its products contain only rocky mountain spring 
water anheuserbusch complained to the federal trade commission 
that coors ships beer concentrates to its elkton facility where 
local water is added 
coors replied that 14 percent of its beer was shipped last year 
as concentrate to elkton where water and carbonation were added 
before packaging but the company said all its beer is brewed with 
rocky mountain spring water 
coors will assume strohs collective bargaining agreement with 
the memphis brewerys hourly employees when it takes over salaried 
employees will be notified later about employment opportunities with 
coors stroh said tuesday 
coors brewing spokeswoman carey baird said the company would not 
discuss plans for the memphis brewery until the transaction was 
completed 
the memphis brewery is one of six owned and operated by stroh 
the breweries employ about 4500 workers and have a total capacity 
of about 24 million barrels a year 
stroh began looking for partners in february 1989 amid financial 
struggles that resulted in more than 300 layoffs and sales of some 
properties and divisions including an icecream business 
stroh agreed to sell most of its beer business to coors for 425 
million last fall but the agreement fell apart in december 
officials of both companies have refused to discuss details of 
the failed buyout such as whether the price or antitrust 
considerations were stumbling blocks 
neither baird nor stroh spokeswoman lacey logan would comment on 
whether the current deal indicated the companies were conducting 
further negotiations stroh president roger fridholm indicated in 
may that stroh was attempting to position itself to continue 
independent operation 
peter stroh stroh chairman and chief executive officer said 
selling the memphis brewery will permit us to effectively 
consolidate our production into our remaining five breweries 
peter coors said the memphis plant is strategically located 
and it has a solid infrastructure and work force in place that 
makes it an excellent fit for us 
</TEXT>
