<DOCNO> AP900605-0216 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
bloomingdales said tuesday its poorly performing 
branch stores in dallas and stamford conn will close late this 
summer 
marvin s traub chairman of bloomingdales said the decision to 
close the two branches came after a regular chainwide review of 
financial performance and future potential 
as part of this review we concluded that it is no longer 
appropriate for bloomingdales to remain in these locations he 
said 
the new yorkbased department store operator has been under 
intense pressure to generate sales and income its parent company 
campeau corpowned federated department stores inc is trying to 
reorganize under bankruptcy court supervision 
the older of the two bloomingdales the one in stamford opened 
for business in 1954 and will close on aug 18 the dallas store has 
been in operation since 1983 and will close on sept 8 
together in recent years the dallas and stamford branches have 
accounted for an almost insignificant 45 percent of the 17store 
chains annual sales by contrast sales at the main store in new 
york city represent onethird of the chains annual volume 
traub said efforts will be made to make the transition easier for 
employees and customers 
stamford personnel will be given the opportunity to transfer to 
stores in new york and new jersey the stamford store has 151 
fulltime 200 parttime and 43 management employees 
bloomingdales owns the property where the stamford store is 
located no decision has been made on whether the site will be sold 
or rented 
the dallas employees will be offered counseling and job placement 
services interviews with other area retailers will be held at the 
dallas bloomingdales the chains only branch in texas the store 
in valley view mall has 229 fulltime 176 parttime and 27 
management employees bloomingdales rents the valley view mall site 
the closing announcements were made to staff tuesday morning 
after briefing employees at the dallas store richard hauser 
bloomingdales regional vice president said that lagging sales due 
to difficult economic conditions led to the decision to shut the 
store 
the store opened at a high level of volume in 1983 despite 
a strong start changes in local market conditions since we opened 
have caused our volume to decline substantially hauser said in a 
brief statement to reporters after the employee meeting 
he did not elaborate 
ann stock spokeswoman at the bloomingdales headquarters in new 
york said the economies in both dallas and stamford have been 
difficult for retailing 
she said the decision to exit those markets was not precipitated 
by any extra pressure from bloomingdales cincinnatibased owner 
federated 
federated along with its sister company allied stores corp 
have been operating under bankruptcy court protection from creditors 
since january heavy debts incurred when they were acquired by 
canadas campeau caused them to seek refuge under chapter 11 of the 
federal bankruptcy code 
in the hope of raising cash federated had been looking for 
buyers for the entire bloomingdales chain last month the chain 
was taken off the auction block retail analysts say they suspect 
federated grew frustrated when it didnt receive high enough offers 
despite the financial problems of federated traub has said 
bloomingdales remains committed to its expansion and renovation 
plans in tuesdays announcement he outlined a series of store 
openings and refurbishments currently on the drawing board 
a new branch is scheduled to open this autumn in palm beach 
gardens in west palm beach fla negotiations are underway on two 
possible new stores in suburban chicagos old orchard and in the 
mall of america in minneapolis renovations are planned at the 
chains flagship new york city store as well as at branches in short 
hills nj and boston mass 
traub suggested bloomingdales could someday return to the dallas 
and stamford markets bloomingdales considers both markets to be 
viable for future stores and we remain open to exploring other 
options in these areas he said 
</TEXT>
