energy futures prices fell sharply tuesday on the new york 
mercantile exchange on reports that saudi arabia is selling crude 
oil at discount prices to its major customers 
on other markets grain and soybean futures were mostly higher 
precious metals climbed copper rallied and livestock and pork 
futures rose sharply 
analysts said saudi arabia may be selling crude at a discount 
because of its displeasure with opecs failure to be faithful to 
production quotas 
according to randolph donney a research analyst with merrill 
lynch in new york the saudis are discounting as much as 75 cents a 
barrel he says it appears they are willing to let the price to dip 
below 15 a barrel 
that will stun a number of countries who depend on oil to keep 
their economies afloat donney said 
last month members of the organization of petroleum exporting 
countries agreed to reduce crude oil output to just over 22 million 
barrels a day donney said the 13 opec countries are currently 
producing 235 million barrels per day 
once again gasoline futures were battered a bad sign for the 
market because gasoline usually leads the market at this time of 
year donney said adding that the driving season got underway with 
the memorial day weekend which usually triggers higher gasoline 
prices 
west texas intermediate crude oil was 14 cents to 49 cents lower 
with july at 1668 a barrel heating oil was 48 cent to 76 cent 
lower with july at 4711 cents a gallon unleaded gasoline was 90 
cent to 176 cents lower with july at 5782 cents a gallon 
