<TEXT>
six dissident members of the founding family of 
campbell soup co disclosed that they have formed a voting trust to 
further their aim of selling the food products company 
in a filing with the securities and exchange commission tuesday 
the six revealed they controlled 174 percent of the camden 
njbased companys shares 
the group composed of three nieces of campbells late chairman 
john t dorrance jr and their husbands said it continues to 
believe that the best interests of the shareholders would be served 
by sale of the company 
the dissident group added however that their position does 
not reflect dissatisfaction with david johnson who became chief 
executive officer of campbell in january 
in camden johnson issued a statement saying im gratified by 
the expression of support from this group of shareholders for the 
companys new strategic direction we are confident that campbell 
soup co will deliver the financial results needed to build maximum 
longterm wealth for all of our shareholders 
dorrance whose great uncle founded the company died last april 
three of dorrances children took control last year of his 313 
percent stake in the company they issued a statement last december 
saying they intended to maintain their ownership in campbell and 
keep the company independent 
