<TEXT>
joblessness tripled in east germany in just 
six weeks and the government worried about mass unrest unveiled a 
broad program tuesday to blunt the shock of the shift to a free 
market 
east german factories will cut hours and reduce wages to try to 
keep people on the payroll even though there is less work for them 
to do said labor and social minister regine hildebrandt 
a new employment administration has been created to oversee a 
program for compensating workers for lost wages and retraining them 
for new jobs she said 
east germany is to officially shed four decades of socialism july 
2 and merge its economy and social institutions with west germany 
it will be the biggest and most difficult stage of full german 
unification 
the effects of unification already are being felt in the form of 
rising prices and growing unemployment as east german enterprises 
many of them inefficient and overstaffed face western competition 
about 100000 people were officially unemployed at the end of 
may said mrs hildebrandt that represents only 1 percent of the 
work force but it is about three times the ated mike easley 
the brunswick county district attorney in the runoff for the 
democratic nomination and will face gop sen jesse helms 
</TEXT>
