<TEXT>
the commerce department has told u s west inc it 
will oppose the companys proposal to supply highspeed 
telecommunications transmission technology for a transsoviet fiber 
optic project u s west said tuesday 
company spokesman ed mattix said the commerce department cited 
national security reasons in opposing attempts by any country to 
supply transmission technology with a capacity of 140 megabits a 
second or greater to the soviet union 
mattix declined to say how much u s west stood to make on the 
project other than to say it would be very profitable he said 
the company would appeal the decision 
were hopeful to address those security issues with commerce 
and hopefully change their mind about that in the next 30 to 45 
days he said 
the technology were talking about is not state of the art it 
is technology two to three generations behind whats used in the 
united states today he said 
the standard today in the united states is 17 gigabits or 17 
billion bits of information per second we were proposing 565 
megabits or 565 million bits of information per second mattix 
said 
a news release from u s west said the fiberoptic line would meet 
growing requirements for communications between the asiapacific 
region and europe by providing international voice facsimile and 
data transmission it also would provide long distance telephone 
communications within the soviet union 
principals in the project include u s west the soviet ministry 
of posts and telecommunications kokusai denshin denway of japan 
societa finanziaria telefonica of italy british telecom plc otc of 
australia denmarks great nordic telegraph company and telecom 
denmark and the deutsche bundespost telkom of west germany 
